{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nTicket 3b4e's close FAILed twice with the unmet criteria surfaced piecemeal — round 1 named one coverage gap, round 2 a different one — costing two extra Gerrit/CI cycles (changes 526, 527). A FAIL verdict should be complete: every unmet criterion enumerated with its remediation in one pass, so one remediation round can clear the gate.\n\n## What\n- Update the completion-verifier rubric prompt (src/rebar/llm/reviewers/completion_verifier.md) to require exhaustive evaluation: assess EVERY acceptance/success/close criterion independently and, on FAIL, emit one finding per unmet criterion — never stop at the first failure. State explicitly that a verdict naming only a subset of unmet criteria is an incomplete verdict.\n- This is a pass-4/prompt-level change: no verdict-reconciliation or threshold logic changes (rebar.llm.completion.reconcile_verdict stays byte-identical).\n- Prove the behavior with an EVAL case, not a tautological FakeRunner test (a FakeRunner test only returns pre-loaded findings, so it cannot demonstrate the prompt achieves exhaustive evaluation). This spans TWO files that must stay mutually consistent (`validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` requires every deterministic scorer named in a spec to be registered in `eval_scorers.REGISTRY`):\n  - `src/rebar/llm/evals/eval_scorers.py`: IMPLEMENT and REGISTER a new deterministic scorer `enumerates_all_unmet_criteria` in `REGISTRY` — given a case annotated with the set of independently-unmet criteria, it scores 1.0 iff the FAIL verdict emits a distinct finding for EACH (>= N findings, each naming a different unmet criterion), else 0.0.\n  - `src/rebar/llm/eval_specs/completion-verifier.eval.yaml`: reference that scorer AND add a dataset case `CV-two-unmet-criteria` (expect: fail) whose fixture ticket carries exactly two independent AC gaps (e.g. an unimplemented function AND an untested path), annotated with the two expected criteria.\n  The eval RUN (external/[eval] CI) is the actual behavioral proof that the prompt emits both findings; `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` is the OFFLINE consistency gate (passes only because the scorer is registered).\n- Additionally add a FakeRunner unit test (mirror tests/interfaces/store/test_completion_verifier.py) asserting the PLUMBING invariant: a multi-finding FAIL verdict survives reconcile_verdict and the close path with all findings intact (guards against regression in the pass-through, distinct from the prompt-behavior eval above).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The completion-verifier prompt (completion_verifier.md, Verdict & findings section) requires per-criterion exhaustive evaluation and one finding per unmet criterion on FAIL, and states that a verdict naming only a subset of unmet criteria is an incomplete verdict.\n- [ ] The `enumerates_all_unmet_criteria` deterministic scorer is implemented AND registered in `eval_scorers.REGISTRY` (evals/eval_scorers.py), and completion-verifier.eval.yaml references it plus a `CV-two-unmet-criteria` case (two independently-unmet criteria). Offline proof: `validate_eval_spec(strict=True)` passes on the extended spec (which it can only do because the scorer is registered). Behavioral proof: the eval run (external/[eval] CI) shows the case's FAIL verdict emits a distinct finding for BOTH unmet criteria (scorer == 1.0).\n- [ ] A FakeRunner unit test asserts a two-finding FAIL verdict is preserved (all findings intact) through reconcile_verdict + the close path.\n- [ ] reconcile_verdict and the close-path logic are byte-unchanged (no reconciliation/threshold edits).\n- [ ] make lint passes on the change.\n- [ ] make test passes on the change."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783889914018227001,"uuid":"42f76df8-0610-4664-beeb-914c89f121ba"}